There are many ways to execute BUlk Delete statements when using JPA.

Bulk Delete with JPQL
---------------------

If the table, whose records you want to delete, is mapped as an entity, you can use a JPQL [`bulk delete`][1] statement, like this one:

    int deleteCount = entityManager.createQuery(&quot;&quot;&quot;
        delete from Post
        where 
            status = :status and
            updatedOn &lt;= :validityThreshold
        &quot;&quot;&quot;)
    .setParameter(&quot;status&quot;, PostStatus.SPAM)
    .setParameter(
        &quot;validityThreshold&quot;,
        Timestamp.valueOf(
            LocalDateTime.now().minusDays(7)
        )
    )
    .executeUpdate();

The `executeUpdate` method returns an `int` value representing the number of records that were affected by the DML statement. In our case, it&#39;s the number of rows that got deleted.

Bulk Delete with Criteria API
-----------------------------

If you want to build the Bulk Delete statement dynamically, then you can use the JPA `CriteriaDelete` query:

    CriteriaBuilder builder = entityManager.getCriteriaBuilder();
        
    CriteriaDelete&lt;T&gt; delete = builder.createCriteriaDelete(postModerateClass);
    
    Root&lt;T&gt; root = delete.from(postModerateClass);
    
    int daysValidityThreshold = (Post.class.isAssignableFrom(postModerateClass)) ? 7 : 3;
    
    delete.where(
        builder.and(
            builder.equal(
                root.get(&quot;status&quot;), 
                PostStatus.SPAM
            ),
            builder.lessThanOrEqualTo(
                root.get(&quot;updatedOn&quot;), 
                Timestamp.valueOf(
                    LocalDateTime
                    .now()
                    .minusDays(daysValidityThreshold)
                )
            )
        )
    );
    
    int deleteCount = entityManager.createQuery(delete).executeUpdate();

Bulk Delete with SQL
---------------------

Another alternative is to use native SQL to execute the bulk delete statement:

    int deleteCount = entityManager.createNativeQuery(&quot;&quot;&quot;
        delete from post
        where 
            status = :status and
            updated_on &lt;= :validityThreshold
        &quot;&quot;&quot;)
    .setParameter(&quot;status&quot;, PostStatus.SPAM.ordinal())
    .setParameter(
        &quot;validityThreshold&quot;,
        Timestamp.valueOf(
            LocalDateTime.now().minusDays(7)
        )
    )
    .executeUpdate();

