    interface Product {
        public UUID getId();
    }

Define another interface for perishable products. Specify a getter method for each of its additional properties.

    interface PerishableProduct extends Product {
        public LocalDate getExpirationDate() ;
    }

Define a product implementation class with the necessary fields. Add [getter method][1] implementations as required by the interfaces. 

    class Milk implements PerishableProduct {
        // Member fields. 
        private UUID id;
        private LocalDate expirationDate ;
    
        // Constructor
        public Milk ( final UUID id , final LocalDate expirationDate ) {
            this.id = id ;
            this.expirationDate = expirationDate ;
        }
    
        // Implement the interfaces’ methods. 
        public UUID getId() { return this.id ; }  // Required by Product interface. 
        public LocalDate getExpirationDate() { return this.expirationDate ; }  // Required by PerishableProduct interface. 
    }

-----

In real work, we would also be adding methods to override `Object` methods, implementing `Comparable`, etc. 

-----

If your objects are meant to be read-only (shallowly [immutable][2]), then in modern Java we can simplify the code with [records][3]. 

With records, we drop the `get` prefix on the getter methods. That [JavaBeans][4] convention is not used by records. In a record, the implicit getter method has the same name as the property. 

    interface Product { public UUID id(); }
    interface PerishableProduct extends Product { public LocalDate expirationDate() ; }
    record Milk implements PerishableProduct ( UUID id , LocalDate expirationDate ) {}

-----

These are basic Java concepts. You should be learning these from a [tutorial][5] or [book][6]. 


