A nice way to sort a small, fixed size of inputs is using a &quot;**sorting network**&quot;.

This network sorts 4 elements, a b c d. Each line compares and swaps two elements:

	int swap;
	if (a &gt; b) { swap = a; a = b; b = swap; }
	if (c &gt; d) { swap = c; c = d; d = swap; }
	if (a &gt; c) { swap = a; a = c; c = swap; }
	if (b &gt; d) { swap = b; b = d; d = swap; }
	if (b &gt; c) { swap = b; b = c; c = swap; }

If you want to sort in reverse order, just flip the `&gt;` signs to `&lt;` signs.

Links:

* [Sorting network - Wikipedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sorting_network)
* [&quot;Introduction to Sorting Networks&quot; - Doug Hoyte](https://hoytech.github.io/sorting-networks/)
* [List of smallest and fastest sorting networks for a given number of inputs](https://bertdobbelaere.github.io/sorting_networks.html)

